"359":{"department":"PHIL","number":"359","title":"Topics in Logic, Information and Agency","description":"Logical analysis of information, interaction and games, with topics connecting philosophy, computer science, game theory, and other fields. The focus is on current research at these interfaces. Prerequisite: 151, 154/254, or equivalent background.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":122446,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["van Benthem, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["van Benthem, J."],"location":"110-101"}],"id":43265}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"361":{"department":"PHIL","number":"361","title":"Social Dimensions of Scientific Knowledge","description":"Study of philosophical issues raised by the social character of scientific research and the relation of scientific inquiry to its broader social, economic, and cultural context:  values in/of science, science and policy, distribution of cognitive labor, trust in science, models of knowledge.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":214750,"primary":[[],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Longino, H."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Longino, H."],"location":"60-119"}],"id":57928}]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"371D":{"department":"PHIL","number":"371D","title":"INEQUALITY: Economic and Philosophical Perspectives (ECON 380, ETHICSOC 371R, POLISCI 431L)","description":"The nature of and problem of inequality is central to both economics and philosophy.  Economists study the causes of inequality, design tools to measure it and track it over time, and examine its consequences.  Philosophers are centrally concerned with the justification of inequality and the reasons why various types of inequality are or are not objectionable.nIn this class we bring both of these approaches together. Our class explores the different meanings of and measurements for understanding inequality, our best understandings of how much inequality there is, its causes, its consequences, and whether we ought to reduce it, and if so, how. nThis is an interdisciplinary graduate seminar. We propose some familiarity with basic ideas in economics and basic ideas in contemporary political philosophy; we will explain and learn about more complex ideas as we proceed. The class will be capped at 20 students.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":211243,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Satz, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Arrow, K.","Satz, D."],"location":"Encina Hall C464"}],"id":45915}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"372M":{"department":"PHIL","number":"372M","title":"Ending Wars: A Just Peace or Just a Peace (ETHICSOC 372R)","description":"Much of just war theory focuses on the justifications for resorting to armed force and the conduct of hostilities. But what are the ethical and legal principles that govern ending wars and making peace? This course will explore the theory of \"just peace,\" including such problems as when a party to war may demand the unconditional surrender of its adversary and what kinds of compromises are ethically permissible in order to end &iquest; or to avoid &iquest; armed conflict. We will also consider the terms and practices the winning party in war may impose on the loser, such as reparations and occupation (particularly transformative occupation). In addition, we will examine the topic of transitional justice, including issues related to amnesty, forgiveness, criminal and other forms of accountability, and reconciliation. Elements used in grading: Class Participation, Written Assignments, Final Exam.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":217738,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Margalit, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"4:15:00 PM","end":"6:15:00 PM","instructors":["Weiner, A.","Margalit, A."],"location":"William H. Neukom building 102"}],"id":57812}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
